## Minimal working examples for common cross-platform tasks

The examples below are intended as ÔÇťminimum viable patternsÔÇŁ that align with the official docs. Where the underlying loader has multiple valid ways to initialise, the examples stick to ArchitecturyÔÇÖs abstractions to minimise loader-specific coupling.

### Cross-platform mod entry and lifecycle wiring

A robust pattern is: call a single `CommonInit.init()` from each loader entrypoint, and put ÔÇťclient-onlyÔÇŁ registrations inside Architectury client lifecycle events rather than relying on loader-specific client entrypoints. This is consistent with the docsÔÇÖ framing that callbacks can be made from your common init, and that client registrations (e.g., screens) should happen during the client setup lifecycle event. ţłÇciteţłéturn17view2ţłéturn18view4ţłü

```java
// common/src/main/java/com/example/examplemod/ExampleMod.java
package com.example.examplemod;

import dev.architectury.event.events.client.ClientLifecycleEvent;

public final class ExampleMod {
    public static final String MOD_ID = "examplemod";

    public static void init() {
        ExampleRegistries.registerAll();
        ExampleNetworking.registerC2SPackets();
        ExampleEvents.registerCommonEvents();

        ClientLifecycleEvent.CLIENT_SETUP.register(client -> {
            ExampleClient.registerClientOnly();
        });
    }
}
```

The use of `ClientLifecycleEvent.CLIENT_SETUP` mirrors the MenuRegistry guidance for registering screen factories during client setup. ţłÇciteţłéturn18view4ţłéturn17view2ţłü

### Platform-specific code without classloading traps

ArchitecturyÔÇÖs docs describe two major approaches:

**Approach A: `@ExpectPlatform` (Architectury Injectables).** This is the most ÔÇťArchitectury-nativeÔÇŁ pattern, but it only applies to static methods and relies on a naming convention: platform package suffix (e.g., `.fabric`) and an `Impl` suffix on the implementation class name. ţłÇciteţłéturn16view2ţłéturn16view3ţłü

```java
// common/src/main/java/com/example/examplemod/PlatformHooks.java
package com.example.examplemod;

import dev.architectury.injectables.annotations.ExpectPlatform;

public final class PlatformHooks {
    private PlatformHooks() {}

    @ExpectPlatform
    public static String getLoaderName() {
        // If this throws at runtime, your injectables/transformer pipeline is not applying.
        throw new AssertionError();
    }
}
```

```java
