This pattern directly follows the official naming and scoping rules described in the `@ExpectPlatform` docs. ţłÇciteţłéturn16view2ţłéturn16view3ţłü

**Approach B: ÔÇťplain JavaÔÇŁ (interfaces / ServiceLoader).** The docs explicitly recommend that you are not forced to use injectables and can implement platform glue with simpler Java patterns if you dislike annotation-based replacement. ţłÇciteţłéturn16view3ţłü

### Registries with `DeferredRegister` and safe access via `RegistrySupplier`

ArchitecturyÔÇÖs registry docs explain why this is hard on Forge-like loaders (registration gated by events) and why wrapper registries return deferred handles (`RegistrySupplier`) rather than the object immediately. ţłÇciteţłéturn17view1ţłü

```java
// common/src/main/java/com/example/examplemod/ExampleRegistries.java
package com.example.examplemod;

import dev.architectury.registry.registries.DeferredRegister;
import dev.architectury.registry.registries.RegistrySupplier;

import net.minecraft.core.registries.Registries;
import net.minecraft.world.item.Item;

public final class ExampleRegistries {
    private ExampleRegistries() {}

    public static final DeferredRegister<Item> ITEMS =
            DeferredRegister.create(ExampleMod.MOD_ID, Registries.ITEM);

